<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="490" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1437,1797,2041]" pageId="13" pageNumber="490">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1834,1860]" pageId="13" pageNumber="490">Remarks.</emphasis>
The distinctive characters identifying the megalopa as a species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1848" box="[1066,1160,1835,1860]" class="Malacostraca" family="Percnidae" genus="Percnon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1066,1160,1835,1860]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="490">Percnon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the carapace outline, the three long rostral spines on the anterior of the carapace, and the short spines on the ventral (flexor) margin of the ambulatory dactyli. It resembles the megalopa of the Atlantic species, 
<taxonomicName authority="(H. Milne Edwards, 1853)" authorityName="H. Milne Edwards" authorityYear="1853" baseAuthorityName="H. Milne Edwards" baseAuthorityYear="1853" box="[948,1436,1905,1932]" class="Malacostraca" family="Percnidae" genus="Percnon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gibbesi">
<emphasis box="[948,1131,1906,1932]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="490">Percnon gibbesi</emphasis>
(H. Milne Edwards, 1853)
</taxonomicName>
(cf. 
<bibRefCitation author="Paula, J. &amp; Hartnoll, R. G." box="[196,454,1942,1968]" pageId="13" pageNumber="490" pagination="17 - 37" refId="ref12003" refString="Paula, J. &amp; Hartnoll, R. G. (1989) The larval and post-larval development of Percnon gibbesi (Crustacea, Brachyura, Grapsidae) and the identity of the larval genus Pluteocaris. Journal of Zoology, London, 218, 17 - 37. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1469 - 7998.1989. tb 02522. x" type="journal article" year="1989">Paula &amp; Hartnoll 1989</bibRefCitation>
: 31, fig. 11), but the carapace of the present specimen is much narrower and the legs are relatively longer. It is difficult to ascertain which of the two preceding, sympatric species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gistel" authorityYear="1848" box="[1189,1283,1979,2004]" class="Malacostraca" family="Percnidae" genus="Percnon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="13" pageNumber="490" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1189,1283,1979,2004]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="490">Percnon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it belongs to, as megalopal differences between the species have not been documented.
</paragraph>
